      <div class="container">
        <h1 id="motiv">Motivation</h1>
        <p>
          At first I was tempted to start a philosophical debate about
          RPG rules in general and a justification of my attempt
          specifically.  But this would soon turn out to take up more
          space than the entire rules to be presented.  So this
          discussion must be provided elsewhere.  Suffice it to say
          that my disinfatuation with current rules available stems
          from the fact that they are overly complicated for the
          little "fitness" they show for representing the genre or
          game world they supposedly apply to.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two major issues that annoy in particular I want to address
          shortly in the next two section.
        </p>
        <h3 id="scale">Scalability</h3>
        <p>
          One of the technical flaws of almost every single set of
          rules I have come across is the applicability of skills and
          difficulties as they progress.  With this rule set, higher
          skill levels compare to higher difficulty level exactly as
          lower skills and lower difficulty level.  At every
          <em>level</em> the rules yield the same probability.
        </p>
        <p>
          One consequence of this, as it turns out, is that using
          rules for multiple actors or multiple targets happens
          (<em>scales</em>) smoothly.  There are no odd jumps in
          probabilities when rules are applied to groups nor is there
          a need for a new type of rule.  Thus separate rules that
          apply to massive or complex (<em>large scale</em>)
          situations are not necessary.
        </p>
        <h3 id="dim">Dimensions</h3>
        <p>
          Many rule sets complicate situations, especially combat,
          because they address the complexity of tactical decisions by
          creating artificial dimensions.  Strength, Combat skills and
          Hit points are the dominating techical terms.  This
          unnecessary creation of dimensions should be avoided.
          Tactical decisions should only be applied to comprehensive
          dimensions, which directly relate to the <em>reality</em>
          modelled.  This is done here in the hope that both
          simplicity and <em>realism</em> can be fostered at the same
          time.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="container">
        <h1 id="basic">Basic Rule</h1>
        <p>
          You roll a <d5/> until you roll a <n1/> and the
          count the number of dice that did not show up a <n1/>.
          That is the same as the number of dice you actually rolled
          minus one.  The higher you get, the better, therefore we
          call it the <em>positive</em> roll.  This roll is dominated
          by the active character, or more generally, the actor.  Of
          course, there is a <em>negative</em> roll that is associated
          with the passive resistance or impediment, which is handled
          in the same way.  These two numbers are subtracted.  The
          result will be a whole number (i.e. a positive or negative
          number without fractional part).  An understanding of this
          rule is crucial, so we elaborate a bit by listing the
          probabilities involved as well as some examples.
        </p>
        <h3 id="prob">Probabilities</h3>
        <p>
          The first row shows the result achieved when you roll.  The
          second row shows the chance that you have of moving up one
          point (i.e. left) at any given point.  Note that this chance
          is always the same.  Then third row gives the percentage
          chance that you have of achieving the result in the
          corresponding first row.  These you could achieve by rolling
          a <d100/> in order to cut down on the number of dice
          to roll.  All but the first column of this row are
          approximations.
        </p>
        <p>
          The last column is somewhat special.  It combines all higher
          results.  You could expand the table to infinity, if you
          wanted.  While the extensions of the first and second row
          are quite obvious, the third is not.  It should be
          interpreted thus: if you roll 91-100, you need to roll again
          on this table, get the result as before and then add 10 to
          the result.  (For the mathematically inclined, this is a
          <em>recursive</em> definition, since it is possible that you
          roll 91-100 again, which forces you to roll on this table
          again and add 20 to the net result from the repeated
          application.  We will see this in the examples.)
        </p>
