        <h3 id="prob_ex">Examples</h3>
        <p>
          The most generic way to roll the dice would be to roll <d5/>
          until a <n1/> is rolled.  To improve speed, several <d10/>
          may be rolled in ordered fashion.  Order them according to
          size or alphabetical color (e.g. black, blue, green, yellow)
          or in any other way you can remember.  With a <d10/> stop at
          <n1/> or <n2/>.  If you lack <d5/>s, you can also roll
          <d6/>s with only a marginal 3% error on each roll.  But all
          players (and GM) should roll the same type dice.  Computer
          applications that make rolling as easy as pressing a button
          are also easy to program.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Assume you decided to use <d100/> and rolled a
              <em>24</em> on the first roll.  This means a result of
              <n1/>.  The second roll (the negative or passive roll)
              shows a <em>50</em>, which results in <n3/> for a net
              result of <em>-2</em>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Another decision is to use the combined table, and a
              <em>28</em> is rolled, which results in <em>-3</em>.
            </li>
            <li>
              A more exotic roll would be the sequence <em>96, 99, 93,
              61</em> on the <d100/>.  The result would be <em>34</em>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Using the standard method, the positive sequence on a
              <d10/> shows <em>3,8,10,7,9,4,6,3,10,10,8,4,2</em> and
              the negative sequence shows <em>3,6,9,4,4,1</em>.  The
              result is positive <em>12</em> and negative <em>5</em>
              with a net result of <em>+7</em>.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <h3 id="adv">Advantages</h3>
        <p>
          This basic rule has several advantages over other rules that
          are proposed in other systems.  In no particular order:
          <ul>
            <li>
              Active and passive are symmetrical.  If you imagine one
              character stealthily evading another, the first may
              interprete the rolls as his actively evading against a
              passive observation of the surroundings, while the
              second may interprete the rolls as his actively
              scrutinzing the vicinity against a passively hiding
              opponent.  Either way, one roll (or set of rolls) will
              determine the outcome.
            </li>
            <li>
              Scaling with respect to difficulty. Imagine that one
              character is particularly string with a certain skill,
              but he also attempts more difficult tasks.  Imagine the
              child character climbing the neighborhood tree and as a
              grown, experienced man climbing an overhanging cliff.
              The child's climbing bonus of <em>12</em> against a
              difficulty addition of <em>14</em> for the tree gives
              the same <em>distribution</em> as the adult's bonus of
              <em>57</em> against the cliff's <em>59</em>.  (We have
              not made any rules on skills and difficulties yet, but
              the will turn out to be additions and subtractions from
              the result.)
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <h3 id="design">Design Guideline</h3>
        <p>
          When designing the concrete implementations of skills,
          difficulties, situations, etc. keep in mind one of the key
          probability of the basic rule.  And that is <em>a result of
          10 or higher has appoximately a 5% chance</em>.  For a
          positive/active roll alone this is at about 10%.  So when
          designing additions/subtractions consider that when
          comparing numbers directly, say skills in a duel, a <n0/>
          will only break even (or win) against a <n10/> in 5% of all
          cases.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the upcoming paragraphs, we will use this to create a
          <em>level</em> system.  Assuming a <em>level</em> for every
          10 point difference gives a good scale.  Passing a level of
          <n10/> higher is not impossible but improbable.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Skills</em> (or <em>Attributes</em>, etc.) should be
          designed as to properly apply to genre-typical situations
          and <em>tests</em>. Whether generic skills and attributes or
          stylized, specific skills are used, depends on the genre.
          Such specialized application is not of importance at this
          stage.
        </p>
