        <h1 id="extended">Extended Rules</h1>
        <p>
          The following sections deal with application of the
          previously explained <em>basic rule</em>.  Many situations
          can be ruled according to the same principles, regardless of
          the specific genre-rule.
        </p>
        <h3 id="dim">Dimensionen</h3>
        <p>
          Skill tests may succeed completely, partially, or not at all.  It
          may take more or less time to complete a task.  Actions or tasks
          are therefore split into several appropriate dimensions, such
          that an action can succeed or fail in each dimension separately.
          The sense of introducing dimensions into the rules is to give
          tactical control to the actor/character.  Sometimes a wall needs
          to be torn down, no matter how long it takes.  Sometimes only a
          certain amount of digging can be done before it is interrupted.
          A very important choice is that of the right dimensions.  A
          predominate dimension applicable to many tasks is <em>time</em>.
        </p>
        <h3 id="combo">Combinations</h3>
        <p>
          Sometimes several people (or more generally <em>actors</em>)
          will want to join forces to expedite an action.  Jointly
          lifting a weight or looking for a clue are typical examples.
          This should be simulated by combining the joining people
          into one actor with an increased bonus to the activities.
          The same is true for attempting several tasks in one
          activity, where rolling many dice would become combersome.
          Attempting to clear away rubble instead of individual stones
          and broken items could be such a situation.
        </p>
        <p>
          First decide what the bonus would be, if two characters with
          the same skill level combine their effort into one.  Then
          the following table provides a way to combine two general
          actors into one.  Take the difference in bonus (<em>skill
          level</em>) as column index and the bonus an equal skill
          should give as row index.  Cross-indexing gives the bonus,
          the actor with the higher skill levbel should receive.
